studies, with
U.S. history, with government.

24:13.986 --> 24:17.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have been constantly talking
about what
this country is founded on with
liberty, justice,

24:17.790 --> 24:22.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the pursuit of happiness,
but it's not
sticking to people. So, we need
to find a

24:22.194 --> 24:23.629 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
different approach to this.

24:23.662 --> 24:26.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: So, one year from
the walkout,
how much has changed?

24:26.865 --> 24:33.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CASEY HILDEN, Student: I have
seen, like,
Muslim people and St. Cloud
natives become

24:33.472 --> 24:37.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on better terms a little bit,
but it's not
been like super noticeable.

24:37.309 --> 24:41.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
UBAH NOOR: There are other
students that are
stepping out of their way to --
if a Somali

24:41.814 --> 24:45.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
kid is walking in the hallway
and somebody
says something to them, they
might step in

24:46.018 --> 24:50.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and be like, hey, that's not
funny. And I
have noticed like that happen
every once in

24:50.422 --> 24:53.158 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
awhile, and I feel like,
gradually, it's changing.

24:53.192 --> 24:57.496 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: It's a start on
what's likely
a long-term project.

24:57.529 --> 25:05.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In St. Cloud, Minnesota, I'm
John Tulenko
of Education Week, reporting for
the "PBS

25:05.738 --> 25:08.807 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
NewsHour."

25:08.841 --> 25:15.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

25:15.781 --> 25:20.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": the
Episcopal
Church's first African-American
presiding

25:20.486 --> 25:26.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bishop explains why acting like
Christ would
change the nation's politics;
plus, an unusual

25:26.825 --> 25:29.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sanctuary for an endangered
butterfly.

25:29.895 --> 25:34.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first, the National Urban
League has
released the 40th edition of its
annual State

25:34.867 --> 25:39.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Black America Report. It's
designed to
provide a snapshot of where
African-Americans

25:39.371 --> 25:41.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are relative to whites.

25:41.407 --> 25:46.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
According to the most recent
report's calculations,
across multiple facets of life,
African-Americans

25:46.078 --> 25:51.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
experience equality at a rate of
72 percent,
compared to white Americans, who
score 100

25:51.517 --> 25:53.152 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
percent.

25:53.185 --> 25:55.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here to explain is Marc Morial,
president
and CEO of the National Urban
League.

25:55.621 --> 25:58.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, let's start with that 72
percent number.
How do you get there? What does
that mean?

25:58.791 --> 26:02.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARC MORIAL, President, National
Urban League:
What it means is, if you compare
things like

26:02.761 --> 26:09.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unemployment, home ownership,
high school
graduation rates, college
attainment rates,

26:09.668 --> 26:17.209 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
median income,
African-Americans, on average,
achieve 72 percent that of where
whites are.

26:17.242 --> 26:23.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are collective numbers. We
also do the
same comparison for Latinos.
Latinos are at

26:23.315 --> 26:29.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about 77 percent, whites being,
of course,
100 percent. So, it's designed
to make our

26:29.521 --> 26:36.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
discussion about persistent
racial inequality
precise, based on numbers, based
on facts,

26:36.662 --> 26:38.464 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and based on clarity.

26:38.497 --> 26:42.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we report this information
every year.
This is the 40th year that we
have done it.

26:42.768 --> 26:46.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we not only report the
information, Hari,
but we also propose solutions.

26:46.638 --> 26:51.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One of the
indicators or
one of the factors is income
inequality, the

26:51.710 --> 26:54.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
gap there. One of the largest
income disparities
that you point out, at least
between black

26:54.980 --> 26:57.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and white families, is in the
Minneapolis
metro area.

26:57.683 --> 27:02.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The average household income for
a black family
there is just over a third, 37.8
percent,

27:02.988 --> 27:06.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the average household income
for a white
family. How does this happen?

27:06.391 --> 27:13.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARC MORIAL: This happens
because the better-paying
jobs, the higher-level jobs go
to whites,

27:13.799 --> 27:18.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and African-Americans are stuck
in lower-paying
jobs on an overall basis.

27:18.971 --> 27:25.043 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And we see this glaring
disparity in places
like Minneapolis. It's also
present in places

27:25.077 --> 27:29.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like San Francisco, where there
is a tremendous
amount of success, a highly
educated work

27:29.548 --> 27:33.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
force. African-Americans are
far, far behind.

27:33.285 --> 27:38.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I hope that what this means is
that, in a
city like Minneapolis or a city
like San Francisco,

27:38.490 --> 27:42.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they won't sweep these numbers
under the rug,
they won't pretend that they
don't exist,

27:42.728 --> 27:47.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and they will recognize and see
it as a challenge
for the civic, business and
political leadership

27:47.966 --> 27:51.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of those communities to try to
address these
disparities.

27:51.637 --> 27:57.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These disparities exist in
virtually every
major American metropolitan
area. It is just

27:57.376 --> 27:59.111 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a question of to what degree.

27:59.144 --> 28:01.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One of the
interesting things
that you mentioned earlier today
was that

28:01.547 --> 28:06.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there was actually an era in the
United States
where African-Americans were
considered three-fifths

28:06.451 --> 28:08.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of a person, right?

28:08.453 --> 28:14.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here you have this snapshot
of how African-Americans
are doing over the last 40
years. And looking

28:14.493 --> 28:20.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
back across this, at income
inequality, I'm
struck by the fact that, in
1976, the average

28:20.232 --> 28:25.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
black family nationwide earned
59 percent
of what a white family did. Now,
40 years

28:25.671 --> 28:28.540 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
later, it hasn't gotten much
better, 60 percent.

28:28.574 --> 28:30.309 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's behind the stagnation?

28:30.342 --> 28:34.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARC MORIAL: Notwithstanding the
political
progress, the progress that's
been made in

28:34.613 --> 28:39.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
terms of high school graduation
rates, number
of African-Americans who have
attained college

28:39.451 --> 28:46.692 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and great individualized
success, this is
a persistent, structural,
locked-in economic

28:46.725 --> 28:48.427 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
situation.

28:48.460 --> 28:53.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I believe, Hari, that we
highlight it
because it defines the pressing
challenge

28:53.165 --> 28:58.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the American future. For
Latinos -- and
Latinos and African-Americans
are almost a

28:58.604 --> 29:05.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
third of the population in this
country -- Latinos
don't fare much better than
African-Americans.

29:05.744 --> 29:11.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is an important challenge
for America's
political business and civic
leaders, to figure

29:11.750 --> 29:18.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out, to concentrate on how to
end these persistent
economic inequities in the
United States.

29:18.690 --> 29:21.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There is a
little bit of
an upside in some of these
numbers.

29:21.326 --> 29:25.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Higher educational achievement,
that's an
movement. Forty years ago, 6.6
percent of

29:25.797 --> 29:30.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
black people had a bachelor's
degree or more.
That's 43 percent of the number
of whites

29:30.402 --> 29:33.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with those degrees. But, today,
that percentage
is up to 63 percent.

29:33.972 --> 29:38.110 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what led to the increase?
And how is it
affecting the black community?

29:38.143 --> 29:43.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARC MORIAL: So, I think those
increases were
a result of policies that began
in the 1960s

29:43.315 --> 29:50.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the 1970s, the Pell Grant
program, affirmative
action, and higher education
admissions, the

29:50.322 --> 29:55.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
desegregation of schools, and
the focus on
educational -- and improving
educational standards.

29:55.761 --> 30:00.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Much of what we have done in the
educational
arena, where there's been a
focus on civil

30:00.065 --> 30:06.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rights and economic injustice,
if you will,
has begun to make a difference.
We see it

30:06.672 --> 30:12.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
indeed in the numbers. But it
has not -- I
repeat -- has not significantly
translated

30:12.611 --> 30:14.513 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to the economic arena.

30:14.546 --> 30:20.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is why the Main Street
Marshall Plan,
which reflects our plan to
address this, suggests

30:21.019 --> 30:26.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a commitment of a trillion
dollars over five
years to begin to address some
of these deep

30:26.958 --> 30:32.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
inequities, is our effort to
say, let's not
get bogged down in just an
analysis and a

30:32.631 --> 30:34.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
diagnosis of the problem.

30:34.599 --> 30:41.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's also focus and figure on
how to change
it. Now, this is what we also
saw in the numbers.

30:41.306 --> 30:50.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From 1963 to 1976, that 13-year
period during
the years in the war on poverty
and at the

30:50.048 --> 30:55.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
height of the post-civil rights
era, we actually
made tremendous change in
America.

30:55.320 --> 31:03.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The poverty rate went down.
Income inequality
narrowed. But then, at 1976, it
got stuck.

31:03.161 --> 31:09.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the disparities of '76 have
become the
disparities of 2016. Now, we
don't know the

31:09.468 --> 31:17.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
effect of the recession, if we
had not had
the 2008-2009 recession, if, in
fact, the

31:17.476 --> 31:21.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
challenges or the disparities
would be less.
We're not sure of that fact.

31:21.947 --> 31:27.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The fact of the matter is, the
disparities
exist. It presents the challenge
for this

31:27.219 --> 31:29.020 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
nation for our 21st century.

